---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Ray Weiss">
  <main class="px-6 py-24 lg:px-16">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-[65ch]">
      <h1
        class="font-sans text-4xl font-medium tracking-tight text-foreground lg:text-5xl"
      >
        About
      </h1>
      <div class="prose-body mt-16">
        <p>
          A little about me. I've been designing games of different kinds for
          around a decade and currently own and operate
          <strong>Conflict Simulations LLC</strong>, a small wargame publishing
          company based in Brooklyn.
        </p>
        <p>
          I've put out about thirty board wargames. I handle most through CSL's
          own print-on-demand operation, and Multi-Man Publishing put out
          <strong>Rostov 41</strong> under their SCS series. Three of them got
          CSR Award nominations in consecutive years
          (<strong>The World Undone: Serbia</strong>,
          <strong>1854: The Alma</strong>, and
          <strong>Imperial Bayonets: For Liberty & Lombardy</strong>), which I
          remain somewhat bewildered about. The board catalog is at <a
            href="https://consimsltd.com/shop">consimsltd.com/shop</a>. The
          digital catalog is on itch, under the same CSL brand.
        </p>
        <p>
          The rest of this site exists because I could never quite learn to
          code.
        </p>
        <p>
          I tried. Throughout the 2010s, when teaching yourself to program was
          supposed to be the thing you were doing, I made serious attempts at
          Python, JavaScript, C++, and a handful of others I would rather not
          name. The only language I ever came close to a real understanding of
          was <strong>6502 assembly</strong>, the instruction set for a 1977 CPU
          that ran the NES and the Commodore 64, and even then I understood it
          poorly. (If you are getting the impression this is an unusual
          direction of aptitude, you are correct.)
        </p>
        <p>Then AI-assisted coding got good enough that I could finally ship.</p>
        <p>
          There is no such thing as ethical consumption under capitalism, and I
          am working a minimum wage job with a somewhat relentless drive to
          create anyway. I may as well use that drive to make things that are
          interesting, useful, or meaningful. Claude has helped me become
          creative again after a long lull, and that probably matters more than
          the tool itself.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>I direct, and the tools implement.</strong> On
          <strong>ZERO-PAGE</strong>, the 6502 puzzle game and sandbox I have
          been working on, I provided the direction and Claude did most of the
          code. The same goes for the rest. <strong>Auftragstaktik</strong> is
          a tactical OSINT terminal I talked into shape in about two weeks.
          <strong>Veridian Contraption</strong> is the Rust ASCII world-simulator
          I have been building under CSL. <strong>Death Of An Empire</strong>,
          also under CSL, is a terminal wargame on the Franco-Prussian War.
          <strong>Buddies</strong> is a Claude Code companion that is also a
          creature-collection game. <strong>CatalogDNA</strong> started as a
          tool for analyzing my own four-hundred-track catalog as Le Rug. All
          of these are projects I designed, could not have written the code
          for, and shipped anyway.
        </p>
        <p>
          I did not "build" most of those. I directed, researched, playtested,
          and shipped. I did not write most of the code. The games, the tools,
          the editorial eye, and the positioning are mine. That version of the
          story is worth telling, and a lot of people will be telling some
          version of it about their own work over the next few years.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you came here from the wargame hobby, welcome. If not, this site
          is what happens when a wargame designer starts shipping in other
          media.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
